ated noun, Middle English <i>revel</i> ‘rebellion, tumult, revelry’ (Old French <i>reveler</i> ‘to revel’). Alternatively, the name may also arise from the Middle English personal name <i>Revel</i>, itself from the adjective above."],"variants":[{"name":"Revelle","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Revell  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Revill","meanings":["English: variant of   Revell  ."]},{"name":"Reville","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Revell  , especially in Ireland.","French: habitational name from any of the three places called Reville, in Manche, Meuse, and Loiret."]},{"name":"Revel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gaston, Henri, Pascal.","French: habitational name from any of the places so named, for example in Isère and Haute-Garonne.","French: nickname from Old French, Occitan <i>reveau</i> ‘rebel’."]},{"name":"Revels","meanings":["English (Cumberland and Yorkshire): variant of   Revell  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Scottish: habitational name from Raffles in Mouswald (Dumfriesshire), comprising Old Norse <i>ref-hol</i> ‘fox-hole’ in a Scots plural form."]},{"name":"Reveal","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Revell  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony<